<sawd:dashboardPage xmlns:sawd="com.siebel.analytics.web/dashboard/v1.1" xmlns:saw="com.siebel.analytics.web/report/v1.1" xmlVersion="200810300" isEmpty="false" duid="mi6pc8rood13bv4a" xmlns:xsd="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"><sawd:dashboardColumn name="Column 1" canFreeze="true" duid="jo6a8hsjojjoes5c" layoutType="specificSize"><sawd:dashboardSection name="Section 3" showHeading="true" duid="190b029g0rfen5u2" showSectionTitle="true" layoutType="bestFit"><saw:caption><saw:text>Explanation</saw:text></saw:caption><sawd:htmlView name="HTML 0" duid="rc2v98vqds0nq1ut"><sawd:HTML fmt="html">[b]What this page is meant to illustrate:[/b][br/][br/]
In OBIEE 11g, Screen reader users are mostly covered by setting Accessibility Mode to ON. However, other users with accessibility needs may not need or use a screen reader. As a result, [br/]these users will not want to have to live with the restrictions applied with Accessibility Mode. These users can see, but need assistance in other ways.[br/][br/]
The displays shown here are a few examples of design techniques that you [u][i][b]must add[/b][/i][/u]    to your designs to make your content fully accessible, especially for users who don&#39;t need a screen [br/]reader and do not [b]want[/b] to use Accessibility Mode. [br/][br/]
Remember these 2 Accessibility Basics:[br/]
1) Deploying accessible content is possible with OBIEE, but it is [u][i][b]not[/b][/i][/u]   automatic. You as the content creator must consciously make a number of design changes to implement the accessible [br/]content features that are available in OBIEE.[br/]
2) Designing for accessibility means you need to cover [u][i][b]all[/b][/i][/u]   user communities, not just blind users.[br/]
</sawd:HTML></sawd:htmlView></sawd:dashboardSection><sawd:dashboardSection name="Section 4" showHeading="true" showSectionTitle="true" duid="6jte3qvj39e5iinl" layoutType="bestFit"><saw:caption><saw:text>Using View Selector and other Design Elements to enhance Accessibility</saw:text></saw:caption><sawd:globalFilterView name="GFP 1" path="/shared/06. Dashboard Design/Accessibility/Dashboard Prompts/Calendar Date Prompt (Accessible)" duid="8ic7u88chncd81ck"><saw:caption><saw:text>Calendar Date Prompt (Accessible)</saw:text></saw:caption></sawd:globalFilterView><sawd:reportView name="Report 1" display="embed" showView="" duid="ms8k20regfperr03"><saw:caption><saw:text>My Report (Alternate Views)</saw:text></saw:caption><sawd:reportRef type="catalog" path="/shared/06. Dashboard Design/Accessibility/My Report (Alternate Views)"/></sawd:reportView></sawd:dashboardSection><saw:displayFormat><saw:formatSpec width="50%" wrapText="true"/></saw:displayFormat></sawd:dashboardColumn><sawd:dashboardColumn name="Column 2" frozen="false" canFreeze="false" duid="6j1jimpto5illrgm" layoutType="specificSize"><sawd:dashboardSection name="Section 5" duid="46gul9in4mgthild" showSectionTitle="false" horizontalLayout="true" showHeading="false" layoutType="bestFit"><saw:caption><saw:text>Explanation</saw:text></saw:caption><sawd:htmlView name="HTML 1" duid="qobt66nm1m1lnj0d"><sawd:HTML fmt="html">[b]The Reason:[/b][br/]
Following are two important aspects of designing for accessibility that require changes from [br/]the default layout you get:[br/]
[br/]
1) The difference between using the default section layout versus creating visible names for each dashboard section.[br/]
2) How to preserve the dashboard context when drilling into one of the objects on a dashboard page.[br/]
[br/]
Neither of these design requirements is included in a dashboard by default. They are easy to add, but [b][i]must be[/i][/b] explicitly [br/]defined by the content designer by using the included properties available in the Dashboard Editor.[br/]
[br/]
[i](The initial state of this dashboard represents the default settings, so you can see what needs to be changed.)[/i]</sawd:HTML></sawd:htmlView><sawd:htmlView name="HTML 2" duid="sl4mafns6o8vtf27"><sawd:HTML fmt="html">[b]How-To:[/b][br/]
[u]Named Sections[/u][br/]
1) Launch the dashboard editor[br/]
2) Hover over each Section and click on the Section [b]Properties[/b] menu[br/]
3) Click on the [b]Rename...[/b] menu and enter a name for the section[br/]
4) Click on the Section [b]Properties[/b] menu again[br/]
5) Click on the [b]Show Section Header[/b] and [b]Show Section Title[/b] menu items to turn them on.[br/]
[br/]
[u]Drilling in Place[/u][br/]
6) Click on the Section [b]Properties[/b] menu again[br/]
7) Click on the [b]Drill in Place[/b] menu item to turn it on.[br/]
